[2026-03-16T17:14:26Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_012dXEjpBdrXiSfduoLuqV4V","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. I need to:\n\n1. Add `MaxConsecutiveFailures` to `OrchestrationConfig` (config.go) with toml tag `max_consecutive_failures`\n2. Add `MaxConsecutiveFailures` to `LoopConfig` (loop.go)\n3. Track consecutive failures in the `Loop` struct\n4. On failure: increment counter, if >= threshold → halt. On success: reset counter.\n5. Reset counter on Resume()\n6. Add to proto/gRPC reporting (GetProjectInfoResponse)\n7. Wire it up in grpc/server.go\n\n\n8. Add config and loop tests\n\nI should also check the proto file and the project.go CLI display to surface this new field. Looking at the task again, this is about stopping the Project when multiple jobs fail consecutively—configurable in cloche.toml with a default of 3 and must be greater than 0. This is a counter-based approach that works alongside the existing `stop_on_error` boolean.\n\nSince the default is 3 and must be positive, the feature is always active by default, meaning the loop halts after 3 consecutive failures. This effectively makes `stop_on_error` somewhat redundant, though they serve slightly different purposes—one stops on any failure, the other on a streak of failures.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5807,"cache_read_input_tokens":30472,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5807},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77daf22e-aee8-40ec-9b79-2fa0d1f74d8f","uuid":"79f8e967-0348-4c56-8194-dcb71a1d503c"}
