[2026-03-16T17:15:29Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MDGbUh6KMkrznYCfhfAML4","type":"tool_result","content":"270-fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n271-\n272-A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to three\n273:host workflow phases for orchestration:\n274-\n275-| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n276-|-------|--------------|---------|\n--\n279-| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n280-\n281-Additionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\n282:automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n283-web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. A task is\n284-considered stale when it has `in_progress` status but no active worker is running for\n285-it (e.g. after a failed run or daemon restart). The workflow receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`.\n--\n380-\n381-## Setting Up Host Workflows\n382-\n383:Host workflows are the orchestration layer that ties everything together. When you\n384-run `cloche init`, a minimal host workflow with just a `main` workflow is generated.\n385-As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows to automate\n386-task discovery and cleanup.\n--\n403-The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n404-tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n405-\n406:**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n407-loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n408-\n409-**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n--\n550-\n551-The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n552-\n553:1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n554-2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n555-3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n556-4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n--\n700-\n701-Without a run ID, shows a daemon status overview: version, run statistics (past hour),\n702-and active runs. In a project directory, also shows project name, concurrency, and\n703:orchestration loop state. Use `--all` to show global stats instead of project-specific\n704-stats.\n705-\n706-| Flag | Description |\n--\n829-|------|---------|-------------|\n830-| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n831-\n832:Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, stop_on_error,\n833-evolution), orchestrator loop state (running/stopped/halted), currently active runs,\n834-and known container and host workflow names. When the loop is halted due to\n835:`stop_on_error`, the halt error message is displayed.\n836-\n837-### `cloche get`\n838-\n--\n861-cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n862-```\n863-\n864:Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n865-upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n866-state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n867-\n--\n871-\n872-### `cloche loop`\n873-\n874:Start, stop, or resume the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n875-tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n876-\n877-```\n--\n886-\n887-`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n888-\n889:`cloche loop resume` clears the halted state after a `stop_on_error` halt, allowing\n890:the loop to resume picking up new work. See `stop_on_error` in the project config.\n891-\n892-### `cloche --version`\n893-\n--\n923-my-project/\n924-├── .cloche/\n925-│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n926:│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflows (contain host { } blocks)\n927-│   ├── Dockerfile 